1
00:00:47,791 --> 00:00:48,875
[ASIRPA]
Right now,

2
00:00:48,958 --> 00:00:50,791
Huci is probably
out in the field,

3
00:00:50,875 --> 00:00:51,916
harvesting grain.

4
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:53,333
[geese quacking]

5
00:00:53,416 --> 00:00:55,916
The flocks of wild geese
in the skies are a sign

6
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:58,500
that the salmon,
which bring the Ainu life,

7
00:00:58,583 --> 00:00:59,791
are on their way up the river.

8
00:01:01,958 --> 00:01:05,250
The name we have
for the salmon is "kamuycep."

9
00:01:05,333 --> 00:01:07,500
Meaning "the fish of the gods."

10
00:01:07,583 --> 00:01:10,666
Or "sipe," Which means
"real food," more or less.

11
00:01:10,750 --> 00:01:13,458
♪

12
00:01:16,458 --> 00:01:19,458
See those?
Get some down for me.

13
00:01:19,541 --> 00:01:21,416
They're "kutci," kiwi berries.

14
00:01:23,458 --> 00:01:24,833
[SUGIMOTO]
Mm.

15
00:01:24,916 --> 00:01:27,041
Holy. This thing is delicious.

16
00:01:27,125 --> 00:01:28,250
It's so sweet.

17
00:01:28,333 --> 00:01:29,958
[ASIRPA]
If you eat too much kutci,

18
00:01:30,041 --> 00:01:31,875
your anus starts to itch.

19
00:01:31,958 --> 00:01:33,958
Eat up, Sugimoto.

20
00:01:36,833 --> 00:01:40,250
The eastern Ainu call
wild berries "salmon berries,"

21
00:01:40,333 --> 00:01:41,708
because when they turn red,

22
00:01:41,791 --> 00:01:44,541
it's time for the salmon
to come up the river.

23
00:01:44,625 --> 00:01:46,291
Sounds like a nice time of year.

24
00:01:46,375 --> 00:01:49,250
Having both these and salmon
to look forward to at once.

25
00:01:58,916 --> 00:02:00,041
[ASIRPA]
Look, Sugimoto,

26
00:02:00,125 --> 00:02:02,708
a bear made that with its claw.

27
00:02:02,791 --> 00:02:06,125
This time of year, the bears eat
nothing but those kiwi berries.

28
00:02:06,208 --> 00:02:07,625
Because of that,
sometimes their meat

29
00:02:07,708 --> 00:02:09,375
will even taste like kutci.

30
00:02:09,458 --> 00:02:10,625
[SUGIMOTO]
Sometimes I'm amazed

31
00:02:10,708 --> 00:02:12,291
at all the things
you know, Asirpa.

32
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:18,500
[ASIRPA]
My aca.

33
00:02:18,583 --> 00:02:21,333
He's the one
who taught me everything.

34
00:02:21,416 --> 00:02:25,666
About the mountains.
The Ainu. Everything.

35
00:02:28,083 --> 00:02:29,541
-Sugimoto.
-Huh?

36
00:02:30,791 --> 00:02:33,041
I'm scared. Help me.

37
00:02:34,666 --> 00:02:38,041
If I learn my father killed
and stole from the Ainu,

38
00:02:38,125 --> 00:02:39,708
it would break my heart.

39
00:02:39,791 --> 00:02:40,916
What do I do?

40
00:02:56,833 --> 00:02:58,458
You should meet him.

41
00:02:58,541 --> 00:03:00,250
We've already gotten
this far, right?

42
00:03:04,541 --> 00:03:06,500
Hey, no matter what,

43
00:03:06,583 --> 00:03:08,041
I'm with you till the end.

44
00:03:11,125 --> 00:03:14,541
♪

45
00:04:51,875 --> 00:04:53,500
[SUGIMOTO]
So, as you all know,

46
00:04:53,583 --> 00:04:56,416
Abashiri Prison
is surrounded by mountains.

47
00:04:56,500 --> 00:04:57,666
And there are
several dozen posts

48
00:04:57,750 --> 00:04:59,041
with armed guards.

49
00:04:59,125 --> 00:05:01,541
The sides facing the mountains
are well guarded

50
00:05:01,625 --> 00:05:03,666
because that's where
the prisoners are kept.

51
00:05:03,750 --> 00:05:05,666
But that's the least
of their worries.

52
00:05:05,750 --> 00:05:07,916
They're far less concerned
about escapees

53
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:10,125
than about people
coming to take Nopperabo.

54
00:05:10,208 --> 00:05:11,708
[SHIRAISHI]
Which is why I was saying

55
00:05:11,791 --> 00:05:12,958
we'll need to go
through the wall

56
00:05:13,041 --> 00:05:14,083
on the Abashiri side,

57
00:05:14,166 --> 00:05:15,750
where it's not as well-guarded.

58
00:05:16,791 --> 00:05:17,791
Here.

59
00:05:19,333 --> 00:05:22,000
♪

60
00:05:26,166 --> 00:05:28,041
[SHIRAISHI] We can only
pull this plan off now,

61
00:05:28,125 --> 00:05:30,000
while the salmon
are spawning.

62
00:05:31,791 --> 00:05:35,333
We'll use an Ainu hut as a cover
to hide the tunnel entrance.

63
00:05:37,333 --> 00:05:38,875
Huh?

64
00:05:38,958 --> 00:05:39,875
[gasps]

65
00:05:44,083 --> 00:05:45,458
[KADOKURA]
What the hell is this?

66
00:05:45,541 --> 00:05:46,750
-Huh?
-Hmm.

67
00:05:46,833 --> 00:05:48,458
[KADOKURA]
You can't build this thing here.

68
00:05:48,541 --> 00:05:50,583
Somebody's up there.

69
00:05:50,666 --> 00:05:53,083
I want this taken down, now.

70
00:05:53,166 --> 00:05:54,916
Why in the world
would you want to set it up

71
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:56,375
right in this spot, anyway?

72
00:05:58,375 --> 00:06:01,291
♪

73
00:06:01,375 --> 00:06:03,583
[TANIGAKI] So you're saying
you want more salmon?

74
00:06:03,666 --> 00:06:05,416
[KADOKURA]
Oh...

75
00:06:05,500 --> 00:06:07,208
What do you mean?

76
00:06:07,291 --> 00:06:09,125
We made a deal with your men.

77
00:06:09,208 --> 00:06:10,916
We all agreed on
three salmon a day

78
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:12,500
for the right to fish here.

79
00:06:12,583 --> 00:06:14,166
Go ahead, ask your guards there.

80
00:06:14,250 --> 00:06:15,666
[shudders]

81
00:06:15,750 --> 00:06:18,500
You dishonor the uniform
accepting bribes.

82
00:06:18,583 --> 00:06:19,375
[SOLDIERS sigh]

83
00:06:19,458 --> 00:06:21,375
[sighs deeply]

84
00:06:24,291 --> 00:06:26,583
Fisherman, make it five.

85
00:06:26,666 --> 00:06:29,750
Or the hut comes down,
you got it?

86
00:06:29,833 --> 00:06:32,875
We'd be better off
just letting the foxes get them.

87
00:06:32,958 --> 00:06:35,958
Chief Kadokura,
please don't tell Warden Inudou

88
00:06:36,041 --> 00:06:37,291
about this, okay?

89
00:06:37,375 --> 00:06:39,208
[KADOKURA]
Of course not, you idiot.

90
00:06:39,291 --> 00:06:40,791
[sighs]

91
00:06:44,375 --> 00:06:45,208
Hmm?

92
00:06:45,291 --> 00:06:46,916
♪

93
00:06:58,583 --> 00:07:01,916
[ASIRPA] Salmon used to be
the Ainu's primary food source.

94
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:03,625
In years when there were
very few salmon,

95
00:07:03,708 --> 00:07:05,333
people actually starved.

96
00:07:06,375 --> 00:07:07,833
So we never waste things.

97
00:07:07,916 --> 00:07:10,375
We've learned to make use
of every part of the fish.

98
00:07:11,958 --> 00:07:14,000
First of all,
you chop off the head.

99
00:07:14,083 --> 00:07:16,416
Then cut out the cartilage
called "hizu,"

100
00:07:16,500 --> 00:07:18,166
it's in the middle
of the upper jaw.

101
00:07:18,250 --> 00:07:19,708
There's a dish
you can make with that.

102
00:07:19,791 --> 00:07:22,083
Sugimoto, can you guess
what it is?

103
00:07:22,166 --> 00:07:23,875
Staying calm.

104
00:07:23,958 --> 00:07:25,541
I think I might know what it is.

105
00:07:25,625 --> 00:07:26,833
I really do.

106
00:07:26,916 --> 00:07:28,166
[ASIRPA]
Chitatap!

107
00:07:28,250 --> 00:07:29,875
Did you hear that?!
We're having chitatap!

108
00:07:31,125 --> 00:07:32,583
So originally,

109
00:07:32,666 --> 00:07:34,916
"chitatap" referred
to the kind made from salmon.

110
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:36,791
It's the father
of all chitataps!

111
00:07:36,875 --> 00:07:39,125
Ow! Stop grabbing me.

112
00:07:39,208 --> 00:07:41,083
[ASIRPA] You make it
from the gills and hizu.

113
00:07:41,166 --> 00:07:43,125
The more you mince it,
the better it gets.

114
00:07:43,208 --> 00:07:44,958
Chitatap, chitatap,
chitatap, chitatap.

115
00:07:45,041 --> 00:07:47,208
Can I use this to make chitatap?

116
00:07:47,291 --> 00:07:48,125
[gasps]

117
00:07:48,208 --> 00:07:49,666
Chitatap, chitatap.

118
00:07:49,750 --> 00:07:51,958
Chitatap, chitatap, chitatap.

119
00:07:54,208 --> 00:07:56,083
Ogata.

120
00:07:56,166 --> 00:07:58,041
Everybody else is saying it.

121
00:07:58,125 --> 00:08:01,041
If you're not even willing
to say this one word with us,

122
00:08:01,125 --> 00:08:02,708
how are we supposed to feel?

123
00:08:03,750 --> 00:08:05,000
I had really been hoping

124
00:08:05,083 --> 00:08:07,125
that this might bring
everyone together.

125
00:08:08,416 --> 00:08:10,083
-Chitatap.
-Hmm?

126
00:08:10,166 --> 00:08:12,083
He said it! Did you hear him?

127
00:08:12,166 --> 00:08:14,750
Ogata just said "chitatap,"
you guys!

128
00:08:14,833 --> 00:08:17,041
Was I really the only one
who heard it?

129
00:08:18,083 --> 00:08:20,166
♪

130
00:08:21,291 --> 00:08:24,000
We prepare a couple of dishes
with the roe,

131
00:08:24,083 --> 00:08:26,458
mixed with porridge,
it's "chiporosayo."

132
00:08:26,541 --> 00:08:28,958
Mixed with potatoes,
it's "cipor rataskep."

133
00:08:34,958 --> 00:08:36,375
Mm. Mm.

134
00:08:36,458 --> 00:08:38,291
It's soft and easy to chew.

135
00:08:38,375 --> 00:08:40,375
So this is
the real chitatap, huh?

136
00:08:40,458 --> 00:08:43,041
This fish is so fresh,
it doesn't even smell.

137
00:08:43,125 --> 00:08:44,291
Hinna, hinna.

138
00:08:44,375 --> 00:08:47,166
This is great.
Really crisp and juicy.

139
00:08:49,666 --> 00:08:51,916
Your name is Inkarmat,
is that right?

140
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:54,125
So, got yourself a man?

141
00:09:00,458 --> 00:09:01,416
[grunts]

142
00:09:02,708 --> 00:09:03,666
Hey.

143
00:09:03,750 --> 00:09:04,750
[CIKIAPASI]
Here.

144
00:09:05,958 --> 00:09:08,208
What do you think you're doing?
That's mine.

145
00:09:08,291 --> 00:09:11,333
If a girl makes a boy a meal
at his house,

146
00:09:11,416 --> 00:09:12,833
and he eats half of it,

147
00:09:12,916 --> 00:09:14,750
but then he gives it back
to her to finish,

148
00:09:14,833 --> 00:09:16,666
once she eats
the rest of his food.

149
00:09:16,750 --> 00:09:18,291
they're officially betrothed.

150
00:09:18,375 --> 00:09:20,750
So that was basically
an Ainu proposal.

151
00:09:20,833 --> 00:09:23,041
Yeah. Why not be a real family?

152
00:09:24,708 --> 00:09:26,208
Oh! Such tension.

153
00:09:26,291 --> 00:09:28,125
I could watch this all day.

154
00:09:28,208 --> 00:09:30,583
Cikapasi, give that back.

155
00:09:37,541 --> 00:09:38,541
Hmm?

156
00:09:41,166 --> 00:09:42,541
Uh-oh.

157
00:09:42,625 --> 00:09:45,208
Guess they're still
in that delicate stage, huh?

158
00:09:45,291 --> 00:09:46,208
[groans]

159
00:09:48,541 --> 00:09:49,958
[INKARMAT]
Tanigaki Nispa.

160
00:09:52,958 --> 00:09:54,375
I saw you watching the prison

161
00:09:54,458 --> 00:09:56,000
from the other side
of the river.

162
00:09:57,833 --> 00:10:00,416
You say you don't believe
Nopperabo is Wilk.

163
00:10:01,458 --> 00:10:02,583
But I think you came here

164
00:10:02,666 --> 00:10:04,458
because part of you
hopes that he is.

165
00:10:05,750 --> 00:10:07,375
You're absolutely right.

166
00:10:09,125 --> 00:10:11,166
Before I met him,

167
00:10:11,250 --> 00:10:14,083
I'd been wandering through life
alone as an orphan.

168
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:18,875
The time I spent with him
was beautiful.

169
00:10:18,958 --> 00:10:20,750
It does still have a hold on me.

170
00:10:21,833 --> 00:10:24,333
But my fortune-telling
has been clear.

171
00:10:24,416 --> 00:10:26,958
We'll never meet
in this life again.

172
00:10:27,041 --> 00:10:29,083
But every time another fortune
came true,

173
00:10:29,166 --> 00:10:32,375
my desire to see him
only grew stronger.

174
00:10:32,458 --> 00:10:33,833
And then,

175
00:10:33,916 --> 00:10:35,375
I heard of his death.

176
00:10:37,041 --> 00:10:39,041
It was impossible.

177
00:10:39,125 --> 00:10:41,166
I'd always believed
it would be my own death

178
00:10:41,250 --> 00:10:43,541
that kept us from meeting again.

179
00:10:43,625 --> 00:10:45,333
That's what my fortune had said.

180
00:10:46,541 --> 00:10:49,625
Then, when I looked
into how he had died,

181
00:10:49,708 --> 00:10:53,083
I met Lieutenant Tsurumi,
who said he had Wilk's things.

182
00:10:54,083 --> 00:10:54,958
Wilk was dead.

183
00:10:55,041 --> 00:10:56,416
[inaudible]

184
00:10:56,500 --> 00:10:58,750
[INKARMAT] Nopperabo in Abashiri
knew the location

185
00:10:58,833 --> 00:11:00,000
of the stolen gold

186
00:11:00,083 --> 00:11:02,416
and was working
with Kiroranke.

187
00:11:02,500 --> 00:11:04,208
That's what he told me.

188
00:11:04,291 --> 00:11:06,916
I assumed my fortune-telling
must've been wrong.

189
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:09,000
I reconciled myself to that.

190
00:11:10,375 --> 00:11:13,750
But then, when I was
drowning in the lake,

191
00:11:13,833 --> 00:11:15,625
I felt it.

192
00:11:15,708 --> 00:11:19,083
I truly was destined
to die that day.

193
00:11:19,166 --> 00:11:21,791
But you, you changed the fate

194
00:11:21,875 --> 00:11:23,666
my fortune-telling
laid out for me.

195
00:11:24,791 --> 00:11:28,291
I learned that day,
one's fate can be changed.

196
00:11:29,708 --> 00:11:32,625
I know this may not make
a lot of sense to you.

197
00:11:32,708 --> 00:11:34,875
But for the moment, I have hope.

198
00:11:34,958 --> 00:11:37,875
That one day soon, I might
actually see Wilk again.

199
00:11:39,208 --> 00:11:40,458
But please understand,

200
00:11:40,541 --> 00:11:43,291
it's not a desire to see
someone that I love.

201
00:11:43,375 --> 00:11:47,291
It's more of a fervent wish
to free myself from my past.

202
00:11:47,375 --> 00:11:48,708
You know why?

203
00:11:48,791 --> 00:11:51,041
Because I want to look
to the future with you.

204
00:11:52,541 --> 00:11:54,833
♪

205
00:11:56,916 --> 00:11:59,125
I still have a job I need to do.

206
00:11:59,208 --> 00:12:01,500
Bringing Asirpa
safely back to Huci.

207
00:12:04,416 --> 00:12:06,291
When that's done,

208
00:12:06,375 --> 00:12:07,791
then I promise,

209
00:12:07,875 --> 00:12:09,666
if you make me a bowl of food,

210
00:12:10,708 --> 00:12:12,166
I'll only eat half.

211
00:12:15,666 --> 00:12:16,916
Would you stop?

212
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:19,958
That food belongs to
Tanigaki Nispa, not you.

213
00:12:27,958 --> 00:12:31,041
[SUGIMOTO] Hey, Kiroranke,
where does this come out?

214
00:12:31,125 --> 00:12:32,708
You sure it's safe?

215
00:12:32,791 --> 00:12:35,791
[KIRORANKE] We dug the exact
distance Hijikata told us to.

216
00:12:35,875 --> 00:12:36,958
We'll have to trust him.

217
00:12:37,041 --> 00:12:38,833
I'm just saying,
if we poke our heads

218
00:12:38,916 --> 00:12:41,916
into the guards' mess hall,
we're screwed.

219
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:42,916
Uh...

220
00:12:45,916 --> 00:12:46,750
♪

221
00:12:46,833 --> 00:12:47,750
[gasps]

222
00:12:49,375 --> 00:12:50,666
It's about time.

223
00:12:50,750 --> 00:12:51,666
You're in the right place.

224
00:12:51,750 --> 00:12:53,166
[SUGIMOTO]
Uh...

225
00:12:53,250 --> 00:12:54,333
Where's that?

226
00:12:54,416 --> 00:12:56,958
[KADOKURA]
My lodgings.

227
00:12:57,041 --> 00:12:59,041
♪

228
00:13:00,166 --> 00:13:02,208
Warden Inudou's orders are firm.

229
00:13:02,291 --> 00:13:06,000
Nopperabo is moved
to a different cell every day.

230
00:13:06,083 --> 00:13:08,000
But that's where I come in, see?

231
00:13:08,083 --> 00:13:10,208
I can tell you
where they're going to move him.

232
00:13:10,291 --> 00:13:12,375
On the night
of the next full moon,

233
00:13:12,458 --> 00:13:15,000
Nopperabo will be taken
to this unit right here.

234
00:13:15,083 --> 00:13:18,083
Building four. Cell number 66.

235
00:13:18,166 --> 00:13:19,375
So the goal is to break in

236
00:13:19,458 --> 00:13:22,125
and get Asirpa
in front of Nopperabo.

237
00:13:22,208 --> 00:13:23,291
If we can manage to do that

238
00:13:23,375 --> 00:13:26,208
and leave without a trace,
we win.

239
00:13:26,291 --> 00:13:29,833
If we fail, they find the tunnel
and Kadokura's a wanted man.

240
00:13:29,916 --> 00:13:32,708
That seems like a pretty
big risk for you to take.

241
00:13:32,791 --> 00:13:34,291
Well, if that happens,

242
00:13:34,375 --> 00:13:36,250
I'm with you, Hijikata.

243
00:13:36,333 --> 00:13:38,250
See, before my father died,

244
00:13:38,333 --> 00:13:40,208
he fought with
the old shogunate,

245
00:13:40,291 --> 00:13:41,958
right alongside you.

246
00:13:42,041 --> 00:13:43,750
He'd be happy to see me
follow you.

247
00:13:43,833 --> 00:13:44,666
Hmm.

248
00:13:44,750 --> 00:13:46,666
What if we discover

249
00:13:46,750 --> 00:13:49,708
that Nopperabo
is Asirpa's father.

250
00:13:49,791 --> 00:13:51,375
How hard will it be
to get him out?

251
00:13:51,458 --> 00:13:54,083
He's had one of his
Achilles tendons cut,

252
00:13:54,166 --> 00:13:57,375
so it will be difficult,
but not impossible.

253
00:13:57,458 --> 00:14:00,041
There's no need to take the risk
of getting him out.

254
00:14:01,416 --> 00:14:04,083
If my father really
is Nopperabo...

255
00:14:04,166 --> 00:14:05,125
Hmph.

256
00:14:06,125 --> 00:14:08,750
You might as well stop
hiding down there and join us.

257
00:14:13,333 --> 00:14:14,791
Heard about you.

258
00:14:14,875 --> 00:14:17,458
Hyakunosuke Ogata,
the illegitimate son

259
00:14:17,541 --> 00:14:20,666
of the Seventh Division's
former leader and his mistress.

260
00:14:20,750 --> 00:14:22,166
For somebody
who just deserted

261
00:14:22,250 --> 00:14:24,625
in order to track down
the gold for himself,

262
00:14:24,708 --> 00:14:26,458
you have
a complicated backstory.

263
00:14:27,833 --> 00:14:29,208
Ah.

264
00:14:29,291 --> 00:14:31,291
Like hell have I ever wanted
my father's career.

265
00:14:31,375 --> 00:14:33,333
What a pain in the ass
that would be.

266
00:14:33,416 --> 00:14:36,083
And anyway, heh,
don't pretend like you guys

267
00:14:36,166 --> 00:14:38,416
can trust each other
any more than you do me.

268
00:14:43,291 --> 00:14:44,875
[SHIRAISHI]
Hey, I just had a thought.

269
00:14:44,958 --> 00:14:46,958
Have you ever tried
using your fortune-telling

270
00:14:47,041 --> 00:14:49,541
to see who Nopperabo is?

271
00:14:49,625 --> 00:14:51,125
Yes, I have, many times.

272
00:14:51,208 --> 00:14:53,416
Why would you do it
more than once?

273
00:14:53,500 --> 00:14:55,416
[INKARMAT] At first, the answer
was always no,

274
00:14:55,500 --> 00:14:57,250
he was not Asirpa's father.

275
00:14:57,333 --> 00:15:00,291
But the more I ask the question,
the more that's begun to change.

276
00:15:00,375 --> 00:15:02,250
It's starting to become clear.

277
00:15:02,333 --> 00:15:03,916
The yeses are catching up.

278
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:07,041
So now, which side is winning?

279
00:15:07,125 --> 00:15:09,083
I just did it a while ago.

280
00:15:09,166 --> 00:15:12,791
Out of a thousand tries,
I got the five hundredth yes.

281
00:15:12,875 --> 00:15:14,500
Well, then,

282
00:15:14,583 --> 00:15:17,375
what if you did it one last time
to break the tie?

283
00:15:22,791 --> 00:15:24,500
♪

284
00:15:43,500 --> 00:15:45,458
[grunts]

285
00:15:45,541 --> 00:15:46,750
What are you doing?

286
00:15:46,833 --> 00:15:48,916
[SHIRAISHI]
Never mind. Don't do it.

287
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:51,833
This isn't going to help us now.

288
00:15:51,916 --> 00:15:53,166
What we need,

289
00:15:53,250 --> 00:15:55,708
is to go find out for ourselves.

290
00:15:58,791 --> 00:16:02,500
[NARRATOR] And on a black,
moonless night...

291
00:16:08,625 --> 00:16:11,583
[SUGIMOTO] Inkarmat, Cikapasi,
Nagakura, and Ienaga,

292
00:16:11,666 --> 00:16:13,458
you'll stay in the kotan.

293
00:16:13,541 --> 00:16:15,208
Ogata, hide in the mountains.

294
00:16:15,291 --> 00:16:17,041
A little rifle support
if we need it.

295
00:16:18,041 --> 00:16:21,333
Tanigaki, you'll stand by with
the log rafts we hid riverside.

296
00:16:21,416 --> 00:16:23,583
Kiroranke, Ushiyama,
and Hijikata,

297
00:16:23,666 --> 00:16:25,291
stand by in the lodging house.

298
00:16:26,541 --> 00:16:29,166
Shiraishi and I
will stick close to Asirpa.

299
00:16:29,250 --> 00:16:32,125
We'll get her to
Nopperabo's cell.

300
00:16:32,208 --> 00:16:34,541
The lights are off
in the prison.

301
00:16:34,625 --> 00:16:37,875
We'll move fast through
the dark and get close.

302
00:16:38,958 --> 00:16:40,500
Toni Anji will take the lead.

303
00:16:41,541 --> 00:16:43,708
The sound of the wind
is strong tonight,

304
00:16:43,791 --> 00:16:46,791
but I can tell where I am
in relation to the buildings.

305
00:16:46,875 --> 00:16:49,958
And it'll also help hide
the sound of my clicking.

306
00:16:51,208 --> 00:16:52,708
[SUGIMOTO]
Okay, let's go.

307
00:16:52,791 --> 00:16:55,208
♪

308
00:16:59,125 --> 00:17:00,291
Who are you guys?

309
00:17:00,375 --> 00:17:02,833
[groaning]

310
00:17:02,916 --> 00:17:05,083
[muffled groaning]

311
00:17:05,166 --> 00:17:07,583
I can't believe
they've already found us.

312
00:17:07,666 --> 00:17:08,625
Toni, what the hell?

313
00:17:08,708 --> 00:17:10,083
Do you have gunk in your ears?

314
00:17:10,166 --> 00:17:12,250
[SUGIMOTO] How did you
miss them, you moron?

315
00:17:12,333 --> 00:17:14,083
Hey, you're the idiots
who didn't realize

316
00:17:14,166 --> 00:17:15,500
they had a damn lamp.

317
00:17:15,583 --> 00:17:17,458
[ASIRPA]
Shh!

318
00:17:17,541 --> 00:17:19,250
We've got this, get outta here.

319
00:17:21,916 --> 00:17:23,791
Well, one thing is for sure.

320
00:17:23,875 --> 00:17:26,416
Kadokura is now unemployed
and wanted.

321
00:17:26,500 --> 00:17:28,291
Yeah, we're off to a bad start.

322
00:17:28,375 --> 00:17:30,708
♪

323
00:17:37,791 --> 00:17:39,708
[TONI]
This is it.

324
00:17:39,791 --> 00:17:42,791
[NARRATOR] The Five Radial Wards
of the Abashiri Prison.

325
00:17:43,875 --> 00:17:46,833
Capable of holding
over 700 prisoners.

326
00:17:46,916 --> 00:17:48,625
And at the center
of the five wings

327
00:17:48,708 --> 00:17:50,833
stands a central watchtower.

328
00:17:50,916 --> 00:17:54,458
From that vantage point,
one can see the entire area.

329
00:17:54,541 --> 00:17:56,041
[SHIRAISHI] If you look around,
you'll notice

330
00:17:56,125 --> 00:17:58,208
that all the windows have bars.

331
00:17:58,291 --> 00:18:01,666
Every single window
except one, that is.

332
00:18:01,750 --> 00:18:03,083
The one on the ceiling.

333
00:18:03,166 --> 00:18:04,250
That's our way in.

334
00:18:04,333 --> 00:18:06,125
We just need to get up
to the roof.

335
00:18:08,083 --> 00:18:10,166
♪

336
00:18:16,541 --> 00:18:17,416
Hmm.

337
00:18:22,750 --> 00:18:24,458
[grunts softly]

338
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:29,500
[saw whirring]

339
00:18:33,916 --> 00:18:35,833
I can hear you, you know.

340
00:18:35,916 --> 00:18:37,500
-[wood creaking]
-[gasps]

341
00:18:39,416 --> 00:18:40,875
-Huh?
-[door opens]

342
00:18:40,958 --> 00:18:42,375
[KADOKURA]
Oh, man.

343
00:18:42,458 --> 00:18:44,291
It sure is windy out tonight.

344
00:18:44,375 --> 00:18:45,333
-Yeah.
-[KADOKURA] Whoa!

345
00:18:45,416 --> 00:18:47,375
Oh, no, look at that.

346
00:18:47,458 --> 00:18:49,125
I broke my cup. Ow!

347
00:18:49,208 --> 00:18:50,375
[SOLDIER 1]
Are you okay?

348
00:18:50,458 --> 00:18:51,916
[SOLDIER 2]
Did you cut yourself?

349
00:18:52,000 --> 00:18:53,291
[SOLDIER 1]
Don't worry, Chief Kadokura.

350
00:18:53,375 --> 00:18:54,625
We'll get it cleaned up.

351
00:18:54,708 --> 00:18:55,833
[KADOKURA]
Thanks.

352
00:18:57,708 --> 00:18:59,791
♪

353
00:19:12,125 --> 00:19:13,416
[lock clicking]

354
00:19:19,791 --> 00:19:20,666
[lock opens]

355
00:19:20,750 --> 00:19:21,708
[scoffs]

356
00:19:23,666 --> 00:19:24,625
[gasps]

357
00:19:28,583 --> 00:19:29,500
[ASIRPA]
Aca.

358
00:19:31,375 --> 00:19:33,416
[WILK]
Asirpa, come here.

359
00:19:37,083 --> 00:19:39,458
Ushiyama, where'd Hijikata
run off to?

360
00:19:39,541 --> 00:19:40,958
Huh? He's not here?

361
00:19:42,500 --> 00:19:44,875
[KIRORANKE] There's something
not right about that old man.

362
00:19:45,916 --> 00:19:48,625
♪

363
00:19:56,250 --> 00:19:57,791
[ASIRPA]
Aca?

364
00:19:57,875 --> 00:19:59,250
Um, Aca?

365
00:19:59,333 --> 00:20:00,500
Is it you?

366
00:20:02,125 --> 00:20:03,416
It's me.

367
00:20:03,500 --> 00:20:04,583
Asirpa.

368
00:20:05,833 --> 00:20:07,416
I've come to see you.

369
00:20:07,500 --> 00:20:09,916
Shiraishi, a match.

370
00:20:12,625 --> 00:20:16,250
[MAN groaning]

371
00:20:16,333 --> 00:20:17,250
[gasps]

372
00:20:17,333 --> 00:20:18,958
[screaming]

373
00:20:23,375 --> 00:20:25,000
[screaming continues]

374
00:20:26,916 --> 00:20:29,583
That's not... my aca.

375
00:20:30,833 --> 00:20:32,125
Intruders inside!

376
00:20:32,208 --> 00:20:34,083
Kadokura!

377
00:20:38,833 --> 00:20:39,875
Sugimoto!

378
00:20:40,958 --> 00:20:41,875
Asirpa!

379
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:46,500
You run. You hear me?

380
00:20:46,583 --> 00:20:49,208
Sugimoto!

381
00:20:49,291 --> 00:20:50,208
[gunshot]

382
00:20:51,875 --> 00:20:54,208
Uh... Why is my gun not working?

383
00:20:54,291 --> 00:20:55,916
Mine isn't either.

384
00:20:56,000 --> 00:20:57,583
You must not have cleaned 'em.

385
00:20:57,666 --> 00:20:59,166
[screaming]

386
00:20:59,250 --> 00:21:00,666
[SHIRAISHI] Do you think
this guy might be

387
00:21:00,750 --> 00:21:01,791
Kiroranke's buddy?

388
00:21:01,875 --> 00:21:03,625
The one Inkarmat
was talking about?

389
00:21:03,708 --> 00:21:06,000
[SOLDIER] Enemy attack!
Get the hell up!

390
00:21:06,083 --> 00:21:07,375
[clamoring]

391
00:21:07,458 --> 00:21:10,666
[SUGIMOTO] Tell me,
are you with Kiroranke?

392
00:21:10,750 --> 00:21:11,708
Answer me!

393
00:21:11,791 --> 00:21:13,083
[groaning]

394
00:21:13,166 --> 00:21:15,333
Looks like he's nothing
but a double, then.

395
00:21:15,416 --> 00:21:17,583
Seriously, who would
go that far?

396
00:21:17,666 --> 00:21:19,583
[SUGIMOTO]
Honestly? I don't know,

397
00:21:19,666 --> 00:21:22,458
but somebody's gone through
some trouble to set us up.

398
00:21:23,625 --> 00:21:26,291
[KADOKURA] You guys need
to stay right here.

399
00:21:27,458 --> 00:21:30,958
Toni, stop.
We have to wait for Sugimoto!

400
00:21:31,041 --> 00:21:32,291
Where are we going?

401
00:21:32,375 --> 00:21:34,833
The tunnel is back
the other way.

402
00:21:34,916 --> 00:21:36,750
I'll take you to the real one.

403
00:21:36,833 --> 00:21:38,375
[ASIRPA]
Hmm?

404
00:21:38,458 --> 00:21:40,333
♪

405
00:21:40,416 --> 00:21:43,041
[bell ringing]

406
00:21:43,125 --> 00:21:44,750
[SOLDIER]
Warden Inudou!

407
00:21:44,833 --> 00:21:47,375
We've got intruders
in Ward Four!

408
00:21:47,458 --> 00:21:50,750
So, they've finally come
for Nopperabo, then, have they?

409
00:21:50,833 --> 00:21:52,250
[ringing continues]

410
00:21:52,333 --> 00:21:53,791
This cannot be good.

411
00:21:53,875 --> 00:21:55,166
Get back here, now.

412
00:21:58,458 --> 00:21:59,958
Hmm?

413
00:22:00,041 --> 00:22:02,166
[TANIGAKI] Inkarmat,
what are you doing here?

414
00:22:03,250 --> 00:22:06,083
Tanigaki Nispa,
I'm asking you to run.

415
00:22:06,166 --> 00:22:08,041
If you stay, you'll get
caught up in it, too.

416
00:22:09,708 --> 00:22:11,583
[gasps]
There!

417
00:22:11,666 --> 00:22:12,666
There they are!

418
00:22:14,291 --> 00:22:16,333
[INKARMAT]
I used a false name.

419
00:22:16,416 --> 00:22:18,708
Told them you'd send a telegram.

420
00:22:18,791 --> 00:22:21,333
He knew when we'd
reach Abashiri.

421
00:22:21,416 --> 00:22:23,833
Inkarmat, what do you mean?

422
00:22:23,916 --> 00:22:26,375
Warden, there are lights
coming up the Abashiri River.

423
00:22:26,458 --> 00:22:27,791
Awaiting your orders, sir.

424
00:22:27,875 --> 00:22:30,166
[SOLDIER]
They're almost to the bridge.

425
00:22:30,250 --> 00:22:33,541
[SOLDIER] Just take a breath
and remember all your training.

426
00:22:38,583 --> 00:22:39,875
[INKARMAT gasps]

427
00:22:39,958 --> 00:22:41,958
[TANIGAKI]
The bridge.

428
00:22:42,041 --> 00:22:43,791
Looks like they're
actually doing it.

429
00:22:43,875 --> 00:22:46,666
Lieutenant Tsurumi
and the Seventh Division?

430
00:22:46,750 --> 00:22:50,125
Never underestimate
an intelligence officer's skill.

431
00:22:50,208 --> 00:22:51,416
Tsurumi.

432
00:22:51,500 --> 00:22:53,791
Has he been watching us
this entire time?

433
00:22:53,875 --> 00:22:56,583
That's the only bridge
to the opposite shore.

434
00:22:56,666 --> 00:22:59,041
Its destruction
will buy us some time.

435
00:22:59,125 --> 00:23:01,958
Everyone,
get ready to fight, now!

436
00:23:02,041 --> 00:23:03,375
[HAJIME]
The bridge is down, sir.

437
00:23:03,458 --> 00:23:04,541
[TSURUMI]
Yes.

438
00:23:04,625 --> 00:23:06,833
This is what
I've been waiting for.

439
00:23:06,916 --> 00:23:08,333
[snickers]

440
00:23:09,958 --> 00:23:11,083
♪

441
00:23:25,375 --> 00:23:27,666
[NARRATOR]
Rear Admiral Heiji Koito,

442
00:23:27,750 --> 00:23:30,208
commander of the Ominato
Guard District.

443
00:23:30,291 --> 00:23:32,291
Second Lieutenant
Koito's father.

444
00:23:32,375 --> 00:23:33,291
Go.

445
00:23:37,750 --> 00:23:40,458
[SOLDIER] We've passed
the remains of the bridge!

446
00:23:40,541 --> 00:23:42,416
This could get ugly.

447
00:23:42,500 --> 00:23:44,000
We would take fewer casualties

448
00:23:44,083 --> 00:23:45,833
if we let the orcas
battle each other

449
00:23:45,916 --> 00:23:47,750
and became like
the disgusting creatures

450
00:23:47,833 --> 00:23:50,750
that feed upon
their sinking carcasses.

451
00:23:50,833 --> 00:23:52,333
No matter how well armed
they are,

452
00:23:52,416 --> 00:23:54,041
they're still prison guards.

453
00:23:54,125 --> 00:23:58,083
Tonight we'll prove that we're
on top of the food chain, men!

454
00:23:58,166 --> 00:23:59,333
Our mission's simple,

455
00:23:59,416 --> 00:24:02,166
capture Nopperabo and Asirpa!

456
00:24:06,666 --> 00:24:09,333
[NARRATOR]
Next time, "Overwhelmed."

